<head>
<title>Why did AFL-CIO chief George Meany help Warren Carroll...</title>
</head>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" background ="/crc/images/bg.gif">
<a href="/crc/images/sidebar.map"><img src="/crc/images/sidebar.gif" alt="Navigation Bar" border="O" 
align="left" ISMAP></a>
<center><h2>Culture Watch</h2></center>
<BR>
<P>
<B><FONT SIZE=4>Why would a &quot;Hoosier&quot; concert pianist
interrupt his musical careeer to found a Washington think-tank?</FONT></B>
<P>
by Laurence Jarvik<BR>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>By any measure Dr. Balint Vazsonyi has had a remarkable
life. A refugee who fled his native Hungary after the failure
of the 1956 revolution, he is a concert pianist who has performed
on four continents, including the complete cycle of Beethoven
sonatas in New York, London, and Boston. He is also a historian,
professor, businessman, producer and host of  television documentaries
on Mozart, Beethoven, Schubert and Brahms, a cultured man of the
world who has lived in Budapest, Vienna and London. Yet at the
same time he is a middle-American family man, a loving father
and husband who studied at Florida State University in Tallahassee,
and who taught music at Indiana University in the 1970's and 80's.
His favorite film is Frank Capra's Mr. Smith Goes to Washington,
he once ran for mayor of Bloomington on the Republican ticket,
and his favorite television program is  Seinfeld.  Last year he
moved to the Watergate apartments and became director of the Center
for the American Founding at the Potomac Foundation in McLean,
Virginia.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Very few Americans have the special gifts Vazsonyi
possesses.  &quot;Balint was a very gifted young pianist when
I knew him at Florida State,&quot; recalls Ellen Taafe Zwilich,
today Carnegie Hall's Pulitzer-prize winning composer-in-residence.
When he performed in London The Times declared, &quot;Beethoven
himself might have played his sonatas much as Mr. Vazsonyi did.&quot;
Daniel F. McDonald, president of the Potomac Foundation, recruited
the pianist for his team of experts after hearing Vazsonyi speak
and play at the Smithsonian Institution.  &quot;He  represented
a special intellectual resource,&quot; he said.  &quot;There's
no one else like him.&quot; McDonald backed Vazsonyi's plan for
the Center for the American Founding because he felt it was important
to &quot;frame policy dialog in terms of the most fundamental
considerations&quot; -- the Constitution and the founding principles
which inform it, principles which have been incorporated into
something Vazsonyi calls his &quot;Reaffirmation of the American
Founding,&quot; a document which has been signed by scores of
public figures.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>We therefore resolve actively to oppose those practices
which are in direct contradiction to the American Founding and
reaffirm our commitment to its basic principles,&quot; reads the
conclusion to the document Vazsonyi has circulated to the nation's
policy elites and thousands of ordinary citizens across America
who have heard him on radio talk shows.  He calls his reaffirmation
campaign &quot;Re-Americanization&quot; in a September 1996 National
Review article. And his efforts are beginning to pay off. The
1996 Republican platform contained a commitment to the American
Founding. And there may be Congressional hearings on the American
Founding in the next Congress if Vazsonyi has his way. He calls
his political agenda simply &quot;American&quot; and says the
issues at stake are neither Democratic nor Republican; rather
they are the fundamental principles which undergird what he sees
as the unparalled success of this nation over two centuries. In
the National Review Vazsonyi declared: &quot;By the other side
I do not mean true Democrats: indeed many of them  might seize
the moment to reaffirm their American foundations. No: I refer
to those whose ideas clearly derive from opposing doctrine.&quot;
<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>The opposing doctrine, says Vazsonyi, &quot;has 
worn many labels -- all variations on socialist philosphy.&quot;
Socialism depends on dividing people: Hitler used race and nationality,
Lenin and Stalin mostly class. The outcome is the same. Germany
and Russia oppressed Vazsonyi's native Hungary for many years,
and his family experienced persecution under both regimes.  He
perceives no real difference between the various forms of tyranny
he endured and sees a continuous struggle between their forces
and the free world. World War I, World War II and the Cold War
were, in the Vazsonyi analysis,  episodes in a century-long attempt
by socialist forces to achieve world domination, opposed consistently
by English political thought representing freedom and respect
for the rights of the individual.  English has given us the word
fairness,&quot; he says. &quot;No other language has yet come
up with even a translation of this word.&quot; He has presented
this perspective in newspaper articles, journals of opinion, and
faxes titled &quot;The Vazsonyi Analyis&quot; as well as in speaking
appearances at venues as varied as the International Monetary
Fund, the National Press Club, the Library of Congress, the Leadership
Institute and the International Platform Association.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Vazsonyi's most important essay, written for the
Potomac Foundation in 1995, is called &quot;The Battle For America's
Soul.&quot; It traces the origins of America's founding principles
to English political thought, and the current proliferation of
group rights mostly to German philosophy. The latter has acquired
bridgeheads in the media and the entertainment industry, and undermined
the traditional political health of American universities. Vazsonyi
speaks from personal  experience on college campuses.  He was
a professor of music at Indiana University and later dean of music
at the New World School of the Arts in Florida. While teaching
at Indiana in 1991, Vazsonyi confronted an organizer who arrived
on campus to co-ordinate opposition to Desert Shield  for a left-wing
group called &quot;the Committee Against the War in the Middle
East.&quot;The Bloomington Herald-Times did not identify C. Clark
Kissinger as anything other than an &quot;author.&quot; Vazsonyi
investigated and discovered that not only were there no books
by this Kissinger in his University library, but that he was a
professional anarchist whose ideal was the Chinese Cultural Revolution.
The lcoal paper did not disclose that the &quot;peace&quot; group
teach-in featured books by Marx and Trotsky, nor that a student
spokesman defined himself as &quot;a Marxist.&quot;<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>Outraged at the deception by the only newspaper in
his community, Vazsonyi organized a &quot;Stand Up for America
Alliance.&quot;  He confronted then-Congressman Frank McCloskey
at a town meeting and took issue with what he thought were McCloskey's
irresponsible statements against U.S. government policy in the
Gulf. Vazsonyi found himself greeted with applause and enthusiasm
by the crowd. He was approached to run for Mayor of Bloomington
as a Republican, a town as liberal as Berkeley, California or
Cambridge, Massachusetts. Although he lost, Vazsonyi had caught
the political bug. He started sending out faxes to his friends
and acquaintances that they called &quot;V-grams,&quot; containing
his perspective on political developments. He joined the Potomac
Foundation as a fellow in 1993, and in 1995 moved to Washington
to oversee the Center for the American Founding, carrying his
struggle to the heart of the American Leviathan.<BR>
</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>[Dr. Vazsonyi can be reached at the Potomac Foundation,
1311 Dolley Madison Boulevard, Suite 2-A, McLean, VA 22101, phone
(703) 506-1790, fax (703) 506-8085, Email balvaz@aol.com]</FONT>
</BODY>
</HTML>
