<HEAD>
<TITLE>Henry v. OSU Consent Decree - CIR</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
  <CENTER><STRONG>
<H2>Center for Individual Rights</H2>
<H4>1300 19th Street, NW<BR>
Suite 260<BR>
Washington, DC 20036<BR>
202-833-8400<BR>
FAX:  202-833-8410<BR><BR>

<A HREF="mailto:CIR@mail.wdn.com">CIR@mail.wdn.com
<br>
<A HREF="http://www.townhall.com/cir">http://www.townhall.com/cir</A><BR><BR>
</H4>
<HR><BR>

                     <H3>     FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<BR>
                              Tuesday, March 26, 1996</H3><BR><BR>


 <H2>            Consent Decree in <EM>Henry Painting v. OSU</EM> <BR>Enjoins The State of Ohio<BR>
 From Continuing 100% Racial Set-Aside<BR>
State To Pay Plaintiff $368,000 in Damages And Fees</H2>
  </STRONG><BR><BR>
 <H3> Federal Judge to Monitor State's Compliance for Next 5 Years</H3></CENTER>

   <P>  Henry Painting Co. v. Ohio State University, a widely watched
lawsuit challenging OSU's one-hundred percent minority set-aside, ended
today when the parties signed a binding judicial consent degree.  

<P>     In a stunning victory for the plaintiff, the State of Ohio
agreed to an injunction against "considering race, color, national
origin, gender, social or economic disadvantage, or any factor
other than standard State procurement policies and practices, in
awarding painting contracts at The Ohio State University."  

 <P>    OSU further agreed to pay the plaintiff, Mr. Jerry Henry,
$368,000 in damages and attorneys' fees in exchange for Mr. Henry's
agreement to drop his lawsuit.  Under the terms of the consent
decree, the federal court will retain jurisdiction over the case
for five years.  Should OSU violate the terms of the decree, the
court may impose "all sanctions and remedies authorized by law or
equity." 

 <P>    "I am delighted that we have won." said Mr. Henry.  "My case
has forced the University to end its decade-long practice of
setting aside 100% of painting contacts exclusively on the basis of
race."         

 <P>    Henry, who operates a small, family-run painting company in
Columbus, had filed the case in federal district court for the
Southern District of Ohio on March 30, 1994, after years of racial
discrimination by OSU.

 <P>    Until 1986, Mr. Henry had done hundreds of thousands of
dollars of business each year with OSU.   Beginning in 1986,
however, and continuing through the filing of the lawsuit, the
University refused to allow Mr. Henry to bid on painting contracts
solely because he is white.   

 <P>    OSU engaged in this blatant racial discrimination pursuant to
an Ohio State Minority Business Act, applicable to all state
agencies, which sets aside 15 percent of total state expenditures
each year for selected minority-owned businesses.  Because OSU was
unable to locate any minority bidders in certain lines of work, it
contrived to reach its 15 percent "goal" by reserving all of its
painting contracts exclusively for minorities.  OSU and State
officials rejected Henry's repeated requests to change the policy.

<P>      "The results of this lawsuit will have far-reaching
consequences," said Michael A. Carvin of Shaw, Pittman, Potts and
Trowbridge, who represented Mr. Henry jointly with attorneys at the
Center for Individual Rights.  "The case shows that the State of
Ohio is incapable of defending the constitutionality of its
Minority Business Enterprise Act.  In light of the substantial
damages in this case, it's only a matter of time before the State's
entire system of racial preferences comes tumbling down."

<P>     Michael P. McDonald, President of the Center for Individual
Rights and Carvin's co-counsel on the case, added:  "The Henry
decree is part of the larger trend that we are seeing of successful
lawsuits to end racial discrimination.  I would expect to see state
agencies in Ohio and elsewhere to take a very hard look at their
set-aside practices unless they, too, want to be sued."

<P>     The Center for Individual Rights is a non-profit public
interest law firm based in Washington, D.C.  CIR provides free
legal assistance to deserving clients in cases raising important
legal and constitutional issues.  Last week, CIR won an important
legal victory for its clients in <EM>Hopwood v. State of Texas</EM>, a case
in which the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit ended
racial preferences in student admissions to the University of Texas
Law School.  

 <P>    For further information about the Henry case, please contact
either Michael A. Carvin at (202) 663-8346 or Michael P. McDonald
at (202) 833-8400, extension 102.<BR><BR>

</BODY>
