<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Hopwood Press Release </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<blockquote><blockquote>
<CENTER><H2><B>Center For Individual Rights</B></H2>
<H3>
1300 NINETEENTH STREET, N.W., SUITE 260<BR>
WASHINGTON, D.C. 20036<BR>
   </H3> 
<BR>
(202) 833-8400<BR>
FAX: (202) 833-8410<BR>
<a href="mailto:cir@mail.wdn.com">CIR@MAIL.WDN.COM</a><BR>
<P>

<h2>FIFTH CIRCUIT PANEL INVALIDATES<BR>
                                  RACE PREFERENCES IN STUDENT ADMISSIONS</h2>

                                                                          March 19, 1996<BR>
                                           <FONT SIZE=+2>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE</FONT><P>
</CENTER>
   <P>     In a widely-followed case, a unanimous panel of the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals held
that the University of Texas Law School's use of racial preferences in student admissions is
unconstitutional.

  <P>      In its March 18 decision, Hopwood v. State of Texas, the Fifth Circuit declared that
"diversity" is not a "compelling state interest" that would justify the use of racial preferences. 
The Court stated that "[w]ithin the general principles of the Fourteenth Amendment, the use of
race in admissions for diversity in higher education contradicts, rather than furthers, the aims
of equal protection.  Diversity fosters, rather than minimizes, the use of race.  It treats
minorities as a group, rather than as individuals."  The Fifth Circuit held that Justice Powell's
opinion in Board of Regents v. Bakke, in which he advocated the consideration of race to achieve
"diversity," never represented the view of a majority of the Supreme Court.

<P>        The Fifth Circuit held further that the government may employ racial preferences only
as a means of redressing past discrimination by a particular government unit--in this case, UT
Law School.  Racial preferences may not be used to redress alleged discrimination by entire
educational systems. 

 <P>       Theodore B. Olson, the plaintiffs' lead attorney, expressed satisfaction with the ruling. 
"This is a strong opinion that clarifies the law in many important areas," Olson said.  "We
expect that the University of Texas will now comply with the Constitution."  Added his co-
counsel, Michael E. Rosman of the Center for Individual Rights:  "The opinion exposes the folly
of thinking that we can get beyond race by taking race into account.  The decision will be widely
discussed." 

<P>        The Fifth Circuit panel was composed of Judges Jerry E. Smith (who wrote the court's
opinion), Harold DeMoss, and Jacques Wiener. 
  
  <P>      The plaintiffs in the case, white applicants to the 1992 incoming class, were denied
admission on the basis of their race despite their superior qualifications.  Cheryl Hopwood and
Douglas Carvell are represented pro bono by Theodore B. Olson and Douglas Cox of Gibson,
Dunn & Crutcher and by Michael E. Rosman, General Counsel of the Center for Individual
Rights.

<P>        For comments call Theodore B. Olson at (202) 955-8500.  Copies of the opinion and
further information may be obtained from CIR at (202) 833-8400, ext. 103 or 104.    <BR><BR>                   
<a href="http://www.law.utexas.edu/94-50569.html">Full Text of Opinion</a>
<P>
Comments?  <A HREF="mailto:CIR@mail.wdn.com">CIR@mail.wdn.com</A>
