<TITLE>Dale vs. BSA: Preface</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY LINK="#0000ff" VLINK="#800080" BGCOLOR="#ffffff">
<a name="top"> </a>
<B><I><P ALIGN="CENTER">Preface</P>
<p>
</I><FONT SIZE=5><P ALIGN="CENTER">Dale v. Boy Scouts of America: The Issue is Freedom</P>
</FONT><P ALIGN="CENTER"><a href="#erler">By Edward J. Erler</a></P>
</B><FONT SIZE=2><P ALIGN="JUSTIFY">&nbsp;</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"></FONT><A HREF="http://www.claremont.org/dale.htm"><FONT SIZE=2>Go to the Brief</FONT></A></P>
<FONT SIZE=2><P ALIGN="JUSTIFY">The filing of <I>amicus curiae</I> (friend of the court) briefs is an important part of the judicial process.  It gives interested parties the chance to submit arguments to the court that would otherwise not be made by the immediate parties to a case.  The Claremont Institute's amicus briefs concentrate on important issues of constitutional law and the moral underpinnings of the Constitution.</P>
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY">In the 1995 case of <I>Dale v. Boy Scouts of America</I>, a New Jersey superior court upheld the refusal of the Boy Scouts to admit an avowed homosexual to a Scout leadership position. James Dale had been a member of the Scouts from the age of eight, eventually achieving the rank of Eagle Scout.  As provided by the By-Laws of the Boy Scouts, his status as a Scout terminated when he reached the age of eighteen.  Because of his exemplary record as a Scout, Dale was offered a commission as Assistant Scoutmaster. In the meantime, Dale had enrolled at Rutgers University and became co-president of the University's Lesbian and Gay Alliance.  </P>
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY">In 1990, a Newark newspaper published an article featuring a picture of Dale with the caption &quot;Seminar addresses needs of homosexual teens&quot; and identifying his position in the Lesbian and Gay Alliance. The article came to attention of the Boy Scouts and Dale was terminated as a Scout Leader.</P>
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY">Dale alleged that his dismissal violated New Jersey laws forbidding discrimination in places of public accommodation.  But the New Jersey superior court made the obvious point that &quot;Boy Scouts of America is not a place; it is an entity which embraces and projects through its organization certain moral concepts and values.  It neither owns or controls a 'place' from which Dale has been excluded.&quot; The court noted that Boy Scouts meet in various places-meeting halls, tents, remote mountain and wooded venues-and that &quot;the benefits to the boys spring not from the 'facility' but from their interaction, training and experiences as a group.&quot; Furthermore, none of the Scout activities or places are open to the public.</P>
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY">More importantly, the superior court rightly held that no one has a &quot;right&quot; to become a Boy Scout or a Boy Scout Leader; anyone who wants to be a Scout or a Leader must conform to the standards and conditions of membership. Indeed, the court recognized that the Boy Scouts &quot;is a moral organization&quot; which requires its members to be &quot;morally straight&quot; and &quot;clean.&quot; Thus, &quot;according to its mission and purpose, BSA has determined that an assistant scoutmaster who is an active sodomist is simply incompatible with scouting and is not 'morally straight.'&quot;</P>
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY">The court noted that New Jersey law no longer criminalizes sodomy. But while &quot;the criminal law has changed. . . the moral law-as to the act of sodomy-has not.&quot;  And, as the court laconically notes, &quot;BSA did not change its moral stance thereafter simply because the criminal law changed.&quot;</P>
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY">Indeed, if &quot;Dale wishes to pursue his own life-style. . . [h]e has a constitutional right to do so, now that the act is no longer criminal. But he cannot compel BSA to continue his volunteer adult leadership status when he is not in compliance with the Scout Oath, the Scout Law and the Statement of Religious Principle.&quot;</P>
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY">The court thus properly upheld the right of the Boy Scouts to maintain its character as an organization whose principal purpose is the moral education of young boys and young men, an education that &quot;requires of them a belief in God (the benevolent and loving Creator) and, through the Scout Oath, the Scout Law and the Scout Handbook an adherence to the Ten Commandments and the Golden Rule.&quot; These are moral principles that are widely under attack today by groups that seek to promote the tenets of ideological liberalism-self-assertion and sexual diversity.  </P>
<P ALIGN="JUSTIFY">The Claremont Institute's Amicus Brief in support of the Boy Scouts urges the court of appeals to affirm the lower court's ruling in <I>Dale v. Boy Scouts of America</I>.  </P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<hr>
<P><a name="erler"><b>Edward J. Erler</b></a> is a professor of political science at California State University, San Bernardino and a Senior Fellow of the Claremont Institute. <a href="#top">Return to the top.</a></P> 
<hr>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
