<html><head>
<title>About the Claremont Institute</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor=#ffffff>

<center><table border=0 width=85%><tr><td>

<center>

   <img src="images/aboutttl.gif" alt="About the Claremont Institute">

</center>

<P>
<hr size=4 noshade>
<P>
<center><h4>250 West First Street | Suite 330 | Claremont, CA  91711 | (909) 621-6825 | Fax: (909) 626-8724</center>
<p>
<p>
<h3>Table of Contents:</h3>

<dl>

<dt>
<img src="images/button.gif" alt="***" vspace=5 hspace=5>
<a href="#mission">Our Mission</a>

<dt>
<img src="images/button.gif" alt="***" vspace=5 hspace=5>
<a href="#programs">Our Programs</a>

<dt>
<img src="images/button.gif" alt="***" vspace=5 hspace=5>
<a href="#membership">Membership in the Claremont Institute</a>

<dt>
<img src="images/button.gif" alt="***" vspace=5 hspace=5>
<a href="#remark">A few Remarks about The Claremont Institute and its Work</a>

</dl>
<P>

<a name="mission">

<hr size=4 noshade>

<center>

   <H1>Our Mission</H1>

</center>

<hr size=4 noshade>

<P>

<body>THE CLAREMONT INSTITUTE finds the answers to America's problems in the principles on which our nation was founded. These principles are expressed most eloquently in the Declaration of Independence, which proclaims that "all men are created equal and are endowed by their Creator with certain inalienable rights. . . ." 

<p>

To recover the Founding principles in our political life means  recovering a limited and accountable government that respects private property, promotes stable family life and maintains a strong defense.

<p>

The Institute's work is only beginning. Today, our state and federal governments spend vast and increasing sums of public money for less and less good. The public sector continues to grow at the expense of the private. Regulations intrude into every corner of our lives. Schools no longer perform. Police and courts no longer protect. Good businesses are being driven to extinction by excessive and discriminatory controls, and as a result good jobs continue to disappear. Dependence grows and opportunity wanes with each passing year.

<p>

The Claremont Institute believes that informed citizens can and will make the right choices for America's future.  Through its books, policy briefings, conferences and seminars, and now through the new electronic media of the World Wide Web, the Institute engages Americans in an informed discussion of the principles and policies necessary to rebuild our civic institutions. 

<P>

Founded in 1979, the Claremont Institute's work is national in scope but gives special emphasis to the problems of our country's largest state, where the Institute is based.  Institute studies like the pioneering 1988 book <I>The Imperial Congress</I> (co-published with The Heritage Foundation), innovative policy proposals such as our 1995 <I>Contract With California</I>, our ongoing work on the cultural attacks on the American family, and our decade-long involvement in the critical debates over environmental regulations and property rights law--all have earned the Institute a reputation for sound scholarship and diligence in the service of constitutional government.

<p>

America's Founders endowed our Republic with sound principles and a framework for governing that is unmatched in the history of mankind.  The prosperity and freedom of America can only be made secure if they are guided by a return to these basic principles as our country enters the 21st Century.</body>

<P>

<a name = "programs">

<hr size=4 noshade>

<center>

   <h1>Our Programs</h1>

</center>

<hr size=4 noshade>

<P>

<h4>The Center for the Study of Natural Law</h4>

<body>The Center for the Study of Natural Law publishes books and reports on the state of family life and the moral precepts underpinning our political institutions. Its aim is to enhance public understanding of the disastrous decline in morality that follows from failed social policies. In addition to books and studies, the Center conducts Pastors Forums and other meetings to strengthen the understanding of our constitutional heritage and encourage active participation in our nation's civic life.  The Center's newest educational program is a venture into the new technology of learning, a CD-ROM: <I>We Hold These Truths: The Argument and the Action of the American Founding</I>.  Available in early 1997, it will be accessible to millions of students and teachers through the Institute's Internet home page on the World Wide Web.</body>

<p>

<h4>The Golden State Center for Policy Studies</h4>
<body>Through the Golden State Center in Sacramento, 
Claremont Institute scholars produce policy papers and reports that educate policy makers, the media, and interested citizens on issues such as the budget, group preferences and quotas, education reform, environmental regulation, 
taxation, health care, and welfare reform. Golden State Center policy briefings have become an important resource for reform-minded state legislators.</body>
<p>

<h4>The Salvatori Center for the American Constitution</h4>

<body>The Salvatori Center conducts academic programs that educate school teachers, public officials, writers, editors and journalists in the principles and practices of American constitutionalism.  The Salvatori Center's programs include curriculum materials for schools, educational seminars for legislators, scholarly panels at the annual meeting of the American Political Science Association, the Publius Fellowships for young scholars, and the newly established Abraham Lincoln Fellowships in Constitutional Government for congressional staff and policy analysts at the federal level.</body>

<h4>The Center for Environmental Education Research<h4>

<body>The CEER publishes reports and curriculum materials to provide America's parents and classroom teachers balanced and objective information to help students understand the complexity environmental issues. It also advises state education policymakers in the design of sound curriculum standards and guidelines. A Scientific Advisory Council of eminent scholars and scientists assists the Center with its work.</body>

<P>

<a name = "membership">

<hr size=4 noshade>

<center>

   <h1>Membership in The Claremont Institute</h1>

</center>

<hr size=4 noshade>

<P>

The Claremont Institute is a non-profit organization that relies on the 
support of individual donors to continue its work.  The Institute is a 
501(c)(3) tax-exempt organization and donations to the Institute are 
tax-deductible.  There are four different levels of membership:

<H3>Presidents Club</H3>

The Presidents Club was formed to involve businessmen and entrepreneurs 
directly in the work of the Claremont Institute, which consists largely of 
promoting the principles of limited government and free enterprise in 
Sacramento, Washington, D.C., and throughout the nation.  Presidents Club 
members receive all Institute briefings and reports, invitations to private, 
bi-monthly strategy sessions with Institute scholars and guest speakers, and 
invitations to an annual policy conference and retreat with policy experts and 
leading public figures from California and Washington.  Membership: Annual gift of $1,000.

<H3>Churchill Club</H3>

Churchill Club members receive all Institute briefings and reports and 
invitations to private bi-monthly strategy sessions with Institute scholars 
and guest speakers.  Membership: Annual gift of $500.

<H3>Patriots Club</H3>

Patriots Club members receive the Claremont Institute newsletter, The 
Public View, as well as selected Institute briefings and invitations to 
Institute special events.  Membership: Annual gift of $100.

<h3>General Membership</h3>

General members receive the Claremont Institute newsletter, The 
Public View, and announcements of publications and events.  
Membership: Annual gift of $25.
<P>

<a name = "remark">

<hr size=4 noshade>

<center>

   <h1>A few Remarks about The Claremont Institute and its Work</h1>

</center>

<hr size=4 noshade>

<P>

<B>

   "Where do we look for innovative, free market solutions to the problems 
   that confront California and our nation?  We turn to organizations like 
   the Claremont Institute, where some of America's top conservative 
   thinkers do their work."

</B>

<P>

--<B>Ronald Reagan</B>, 40th President of the United States

<P>

<hr size=4 noshade>

<P>

<B>

   "Right now there are very few groups that are effective against the liberal 
   policies and special interests that are corrupting our system.  Fortunately, 
   the Claremont Institute is an exception.  That's why I have chosen to become 
   a part of their efforts."

</B>

<P>

--<B>Bruce Herschensohn</B>, Distinguished Fellow, The Claremont Institute

<P>

<hr size=4 noshade>

<P>

<B>

   "The Claremont Institute is leading the fight for property rights, and to reduce 
   onerous and destructive regulation on the business community."

</B>

<P>

--<B>Donald Moe</B>, Senior Vice President, The Santa Margarita 
Company; Board Member, The Claremont Institute

<P>

