<BR>
<UL>
<LI><a href="/nationalreview/27jan97/inprint.html">January 27, 1997</a> Con Job: <B>Ramesh Ponnuru</b> parries Jacob Heilbrunn's attempt to drive a wedge between theocons and neocons attacking <I>First Things</I>' End of Democracy symposium.
<P>
<LI><a href="/nationalreview/31dec96/inprint.html">December 31, 1996</a> Bread & Circuses: <B>Kate O'Beirne</B> advises the Republicans to avoid tinkering with the Consumer Price Index.
<P>
<LI><a href="/nationalreview/23dec96/inprint.html">December 23, 1996</a> Rising Stars: <B>Robert Novak</B> casts his eye over the new generation of conservative leaders.
<P>
<LI><a href="/nationalreview/09dec96/inprint.html">December 9, 1996</a> Who Lost the Election? Inside the Campaign: <B>Ramesh Ponnuru</B> looks inside the late unlamented Dole campaign and finds nothing there, as expected.
<P>
<LI><a href="/nationalreview/25nov96/inprint.html">November 25, 1996</a> Clinton's Crowning Victory: <B>Kate O'Beirne</B>, <B>Rich Lowry</B>, and <B>Ramesh Ponnuru</B> interpret the election results.
<P>
<LI><a href="/nationalreview/11nov96/inprint.html">November 11, 1996</a> Riding High: <B>Kate O'Beirne</B> watches Bill Clinton busily forge his coalition.
<P>
<LI><a href="/nationalreview/28oct96/inprint.html">October 28, 1996</a> Kemp's World: <B>Ramesh Ponnuru</B> is bemused by Jack Kemp on the hustings.
<P>
<LI><a href="/nationalreview/14oct96/inprint.html">October 14, 1996</a> Rotten to the Gore: <B>Rich Lowry</B> notes that Al Gore's life has been less about liberal politics and more about self-promotion.
<P>
<LI><a href="/nationalreview/30sept96/inprint.html">September 30, 1996</a> Dole Patrol: <B>Rich Lowry</B> follows Bob Dole's campaign trail steps and missteps.
<P>
<LI><a href="/nationalreview/16sept96/inprint.html">September 16, 1996</a> See Jack Grow: <B>Richard  Brookhiser</B> notes that although Jack Kemp may have revitalized the Dole campaign, he may also be tough to handle.
<P>
<LI><a href="/nationalreview/02sept96/inprint.html">September 2, 1996</a> Rolling Back Quotas: <B>Rich  Lowry</B> introduces Ward Connerly, the prime mover behind the California Civil Rights Initiative.
<P>
<LI><a href="/nationalreview/12aug96/inprint.html">August 12,1996</a> Jumping Ship: <B>Rich  Lowry</B> on the disheartening effect the Dole campaign is having on Congressional Republicans.
<P>
<LI><a href="/nationalreview/29july96/inprint.html">July 29, 1996</a> See How They Run: <B>Rich  Lowry</B> on Bob Dole's potential running mates.
<P>
<LI><a href="/nationalreview/15july96/inprint.html">July 15, 1996</a> Capital Offense: <B>John Dizard</B> on the decline and fall of Washington, D.C.
<P>
<LI><a href="/nationalreview/01july96/contents.html">July 1, 1996</a> Is the War on Drugs Really Lost?  400 Readers Respond with a reply by <B>Wm. F. Buckley, Jr</B>.
<P>
<LI><a href="/nationalreview/17june96/contents.html">June 17, 1996</a> Rude Awakening: <b>David Satter</b> on the revival of Russia's Communists.
<P>
<LI><a href="/nationalreview/03june96/contents.html">June 3, 1996</a> The Unnecessary GOP Meltdown: <b>Kate O'Beirne</b> and <b>Ramesh Ponnuru</b> on Republican skittishness.
<P>
<LI><a href="/nationalreview/20may96/contents.html">May 20, 1996</a> Crossroads: <b>Lawrence Kudlow</b> examines the confluence of politcs and the market.
<P>
<LI><a href="/nationalreview/06may96/contents.html">May 6, 1996</a> Reagan's Spoiled Children: <b>Ramesh Ponnuru</b> sees the future of the conservative movement threatened by infighting.
<P>
<LI><a href="/nationalreview/22apr96/contents.html">April 22, 1996</a> Liberalism and Terror: <b>Conor Cruise O'Brien</b> on the former's inability to deal with the latter.
<P>
<LI><a href="/nationalreview/08apr96/contents.html">April 8, 1996</a> How Jackie Robinson Desegregated America: <b>Steve Sailer</b> on how competition can transform self-interest into an engine for racial fairness.
<P>
<LI><a href="/nationalreview/25mar96/contents.html">March 25, 1996</a> The America We Seek: A Statement of Pro-Life Principle and Concern.
<P>
<LI><a href="/nationalreview/11mar96/contents.html">March 11, 1996</a> Your 100 Best Conservative Movies. By <b>Spencer Warren</b>. 'Nuff said.
<P>
<LI><a href="/nationalreview/26feb96/contents.html">February 26, 1996</a> Founding Father: <b>Richard Brookhiser</b> on George Washington's many merits.
<P>
<LI><a href="/nationalreview/12feb96/contents.html">February 12, 1996</a> The War on Drugs is Lost. Our noted manifesto.
<P>
<LI><A HREF="/nationalreview/16jan96/contents.html">January 29, 1996</A> Rich and Spoiler: <b>Rich Lowry</b> on the appeal of Steve Forbes and the popularity of his flat tax idea.
<P>
<LI><A HREF="/nationalreview/31dec95/contents.html">December 31, 1995</A> Bread & Circuses: <b>Kate O'Beirne</b> looks at what the Republican congress accomplished in '95 and what the future holds.
<P>
<LI><A HREF="/nationalreview/25dec95/contents.html">December 25, 1995</A> Yalta in the Balkans: <b>Peter Rodman</b> on how the Clinton Administration traded NATO enlargement for Russia's assistance in the former Yugoslavia.
<P>
<LI><A HREF="/nationalreview/11dec95/contents.html">December 11, 1995</A> Standing Athwart: <b>William F. Buckley, Jr</b>. looks back on forty years of fighting the good fight.
<P>
<LI><A HREF="/nationalreview/13nov95/contents.html">November 27, 1995</A> Dying of the Light: <b>Midge Decter</b> on the astonishing rate at which homosexuals continue to contract AIDS.
<P>
<LI><A HREF="/nationalreview/06nov95/contents.html">November 6, 1995</A> The Two Nations: An editorial on what the Simpson verdict intimates for race relations.
<P>
<LI><A HREF="/nationalreview/23oct95/contents.html">October 23, 1995</A> Beware of Greeks: <b>Taki Theodoracopulos</b> recalls his interview with James Jones and the drama which followed.
<P>
<LI><A HREF="/nationalreview/09oct95/contents.html">October 9, 1995</A> Myth of the Racist Cabbie: <b>Dinesh D'Souza</b> explains the difference between racism and discrimination, and suggests that some of the latter may be entirely rational.
<P>
<LI><A HREF="/nationalreview/25sep95/contents.html">September 25, 1995</A> The Little Engine that Couldn't: <b>Stephen Moore</b> examines the spine of the Republican body politic and wonders whether it will make it through the coming budget battles.
<P>
<LI><A HREF="/nationalreview/11sep95/contents.html">September 11, 1995</A> Fear Itself: <b>Rich Lowry</b> scrutizes Democratic charges of Republican laxity on public health matters and finds them lacking. 
<P>
<LI><A HREF="/nationalreview/28aug95/contents.html">August 28, 1995</A> From the Editor: <b>John O'Sullivan</b> on Japanese war crimes, Ross Perot and the GOP, and the effectiveness of Bob Packwood's methods on securing a first date.
<P>
<LI><A HREF="/nationalreview/14aug95/contents.html">August 14, 1995</A> Affirmative Inaction: <b>Ramesh Ponnuru</b> laments the GOP's lack of leadership on racial prefrences...The Cigar Revisited: <b>William A. Rusher</b> defends the conservative virtues of a good smoke.
<P>
<LI><A HREF="/nationalreview/21july95/contents.html">July 31, 1995</A> The 101st Senator: <b>Rich Lowry</b> gives Bob Dole's inordinately powerful staffer, Sheila Burke, a once over...<b>Jeffrey Hart</b> reviews David Gelernter's <I>1939:The Lost World of the Fair</I> and gives a qualified thumbs up.  
<P>
<LI><A HREF="/nationalreview/10july95/contents.html">July 10, 1995</A> Legalizing Drugs: Just Say Yes: An Interview with <b>Michael S. Gazzaniga</b>...The Gimlet Eye: <b>Andrew Ferguson</b> on Robert McNamara as a Washington phenomenon.
<P>
<LI><A HREF="/nationalreview/26june95/contents.html">June 26, 1995</A> Saving Gramm's Campaign: <b>Richard Brookhiser</b> explores the inner workings of a presidential canmpaign...<b>Florence King</b> considers, briefly, America's shrinking attention span. 

</UL>
