<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>McCrery - Dear Colleague Letter</TITLE>

</HEAD>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" link="#2F4F2F" vlink="#3232CD">

<strong>JIM McCRERY<br>
5th District, Louisiana</strong>
<p>
COMMITTEE ON WAYS AND MEANS
<hr>
<P><center>
<font size=4><strong><em>Congress of the United States</em></font><br>
<font size=3><em>House of Representatives<br>
Washington, DC  20515-1805</em></strong></font></center>
<P>
<center>January 27, 1995
<p>
<font size=3><strong>ENCOURAGE SAVINGS AND PROMOTE ECONOMIC GROWTH</strong></font>
</center>

<P>
Dear Colleague:
<P>
I have re-introduced the Individual Investment Account Act-H.R.
328 in the 104th Congress-to make long overdue improvements to
our tax law to boost personal savings.
<P>
This legislation provides for unlimited tax deductions for IRA-type
savings, tax-deferred earnings growth, no penalty tax, no forced
distribution at any age, and no income tax or estate tax at death.
 Ordinary income taxes are paid solely when withdrawals take place
from the Investment Account into the first purchase of a principal
residence and the tax-free roll-over into the Investment Account
of the proceeds from the sale of a principal residence.
<P>
As we all know, personal savings is far too low for our nation's
economy to achieve robust economic growth and increased national
wealth.  A major impeding factor is the senseless &quot;double
tax&quot; on savings imposed by the ordinary income tax.  Under
the &quot;double tax,&quot; personal income is first taxed when
earned.  Then, if the resulting post-tax disposable income is
used for consumption of goods and services, no further federal
income taxes are imposed.  If the income is saved, the earnings
that accrue to the savings are taxed again.  Thus, the cost of
saving is higher than the cost of consumption-a policy which needlessly
restricts both savings and growth.
<P>
I believe the differential in the tax treatment of savings vs.
consumption can best be resolved by creating a universal, unlimited,
tax-deductible, IRA-type plan as provided in H.R. 328.  This bill
removes the income tax's recognized bias against saving.  I urge
you to read the article on this plan written by syndicated columnist
Donald Lambro and provided on the back of this Dear Colleague.
 (H.R. 3179 of the 103rd Congress is identical to H.R. 328.)
<P>
If you are interested in encouraging savings and promoting economic
growth, please call Heather Hanson of my staff (x52777) to join
me as a cosponsor of H.R. 328.
<P>
Sincerely,<p>
<em>
Jim McCrery<br>
Member of Congress
</em>
<p>
<hr>
[<a href="/savers/">Home</a>], [<a href="/savers/library.html">Library</a>], 
Legislation Listed By: [<a 
href="/savers/legnum.html">Bill No.</a>] or [<a href="/savers/legname.html">Sponsor</a>]
