<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Power of the Pen...</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<font size=5>
<center>Constituent Clout...The Power of the Pen...</center><br>
</font><hr>
<p>
During a recent symposium on various tax matters to be considered by Congress, an opinion was expressed by a participant that &quot;there's a certain hopelessness about trying to write a letter to Members of Congress and expecting action.&quot;<br>
<p>
Another symposium participant with extensive lobbying experience on the Hill responded as follows as recorded by a court reporter:<br>
<p>
<blockquote>&quot;Let me tell you something:  10 letters, 20 letters to a House Member from his District is a wake up call like you can't believe.  Fifteen telephone calls on one issue in a given two-day period is a wake up call like you can't believe.<br>
<p>
What is very sad about this country is that they---a lot of folks, not everyone---have no clue of the influence they have on their Members of Congress either in the House or the Senate.  Let me tell you, if they sit down and write a letter or they pick up the phone and call that guy, they have a person there who takes count of the calls and what the subject is.  And, that's given to the Member every day, even if he doesn't---does not speak to the Member.<br>
<p>
And all the lobbyists in the world could call in 20 times a day---and I hate to say this in front of my superiors here, but I don't have the influence that 10 people out there calling in from his District who votes in his District will have on that Member.  And that's a definite wake-up call.  All they have to do is pick up the phone.  All they have to do is write a letter.&quot;<br>
<p>
</blockquote>
This commentary is absolutely correct.  You, and your fellow voter/taxpayers within your Congressional District have enormous clout.  Far too often this latent power lies dormant!<br>
<P>
<hr>
[<a href="/savers/">Home</a>]
</BODY>
