permit nonemployed spouses a full IRA deduction, etc. (Mr. Baker of CA)
<br>
<li><a href="/savers/legislation/hr1042.html">H.R. 1042</a> To provide that no capital gains tax shall apply to
individuals. (Mr. Crane)
<br>
<li><a href="/savers/legislation/hr1322.html">H.R. 1322</a> To allow a $100,000 lifetime deduction for net capital
gain. (Mr. Schumer)
<br>
<li><a href="/savers/legislation/hr1389.html">H.R. 1389</a> To expand availability of, and amount of, 
deductible IRA contributions, etc. (Mr. Hinchey)
<br>
<li><a href="/savers/legislation/hr1652.html">H.R. 1652</a> To allow individuals who have reached age 59 1/2 
to contribute to an IRA without regard to their compensation. (Mr. Shays)
<br>
<li><a href="/savers/legislation/hr1780.html">H.R. 1780</a> To impose a flat tax only on the earned income of
individuals and the business taxable income of corporations, and for other purposes. (Mr. Souder)
<br>
<li><a href="/savers/legislation/hr2060.html">H.R. 2060</a> or (<a 
href="/savers/legislation/blcflat.html">Summary</a>) Freedom and Fairness 
Restoration Act of 1995 (aka: Flat Tax) (Mr. Armey) 
<br>
<li><a href="/savers/legislation/hr2083.html">H.R. 2083</a> To provide for a tax reduction in the case of low
economic growth. (Mr. Obey)
<br>
