<IMG SRC="../images/nwe.redrule.gif" WIDTH=520 HEIGHT=24 ALIGN=MIDDLE border=0><BR><NOBR><font size=-1>Published in Washington, D.C.&#009;<B>February 9, 1997 -- Edition</B>&#009;<IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=0>"America's Newspaper"<BR></font></NOBR><A HREF="buttons.3.gif.map"><MAP NAME="clientmap3"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="436,1,519,18" HREF="../watch/watch.html"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="351,1,428,16" HREF="../letters/letters.html"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="263,0,345,19" HREF="exclusive.html"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="177,1,257,18" HREF="culture.html"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="90,0,172,19" HREF="#linkTOP"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="2,1,86,18" HREF="../index.html"></MAP><IMG SRC="images/buttons.3.gif" WIDTH=520 HEIGHT=19 ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="Navigation Bar graphic, see text links below." border=0 USEMAP="#clientmap3" ISMAP></A><BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif"  ALIGN=top WIDTH=0 HEIGHT=8><BR><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=520><TR ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top> <TD ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top COLSPAN="3" ROWSPAN="5"><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=325><TR ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top> <TD ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1"><FONT SIZE=6>Huang give top-secret<BR>clearance after DNC move<BR></FONT><ALIGN=Left><HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=100% ALIGN=Center NOSHADE><ALIGN=Left>By Jerry Seper<BR><font size=1>THE WASHINGTON TIMES<HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=100% ALIGN=Center NOSHADE></font><IMG SRC="../images/cap.J.gif" alt=J border=0 align=left height=34>ohn Huang was issued a "consultant top-secret" security clearance after he resigned as a Commerce Department official to take over as a fund-raiser at the Democratic National Committee, department records show. <BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>The clearance means the former Lippo Group executive, now the focus of an FBI probe into possible economic-espionage and national-security concerns, held top-secret clearances for three years, although he worked at Commerce for only 18 months.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>"We'd certainly like to know how that happened and why," said one congressional investigator looking into Mr. Huang's ties to a growing scandal over foreign-linked campaign contributions. "It is very curious, and perhaps even unprecedented."<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>The top-secret clearance, requested by Commerce Department executives, was issued by the Defense Industrial Security Clearance Office (DISCO) on Dec. 12, 1995 -- after Mr. Huang left the department as deputy assistant secretary for international economic policy and before he reported to work at the DNC.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>It remained in effect until Dec. 9, 1996, DISCO records show, although it is not clear how he used the clearance as a top DNC fund-raiser. It could have gained him access to classified meetings and documents.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Mr. Huang initially was issued a top-secret security clearance in January 1994, five months before he resigned as a top executive at the Indonesia-based Lippo Group, a multibillion-dollar investment conglomerate, to go to Commerce. He was a vice president at Lippo Bank in Los Angeles and resigned in July 1994 to take over as deputy assistant secretary at Commerce.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Commerce and DNC records are not clear as to when Mr. Huang actually left the government and began as a fund-raiser. The DNC said he started work on Dec. 4, 1995. Commerce said he left the department on Jan. 17, 1996.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>A Commerce memo dated Jan. 31, 1994, said Mr. Huang was granted an interim top-secret clearance before his arrival at Commerce "due to the critical need for his expertise in the new administration for Secretary [Ronald H.] Brown."<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>The same reasoning was used in December 1995, when the assistant commerce secretary, Charles F. Meissner, asked in a "request for personnel action" that Mr. Huang be retained as a consultant despite his pending departure to the DNC.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Mr. Meissner said Mr. Huang would help in the transition period in finding a replacement and his "expertise" on the Asia-Pacific region would be vital to the department's commercial policy planning there. Records show the consultancy eventually was not approved, but the top-secret clearance was granted and remained valid for a year.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Congressional investigators want to know if there was concern at Commerce of a possible conflict of interest regarding Mr. Huang's role as a DNC fund-raiser while serving as a department consultant with a top-secret clearance.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>They also are trying to determine if Mr. Huang was given classified information that may have been leaked to Lippo. Telephone records show that while at Commerce, he made and received dozens of calls from Lippo lobbyists and executives while he worked on sensitive trade missions.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Mr. Meissner was among 34 persons, including Mr. Brown, killed in an April plane crash in Croatia.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Mr. Huang, who became a U.S. citizen in 1976, is believed to have returned to California. He previously has denied any wrongdoing. As a DNC fund-raiser, he solicited $2.5 million from contributors with Asian business links, $1.5 million of which has been returned.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Meanwhile, Rep. Gerald B.H. Solomon, New York Republican and chairman of the House Rules Committee, on Jan. 29 asked Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright for copies of letters written by Clinton supporters Ernest G. Green and Charles Yah Lin Trie to help a Chinese arms dealer, Wang Jun, get a visa to visit the United States.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Mr. Green, managing director at Lehman Brothers Inc. in Washington and a former Little Rock resident, and Mr. Trie, an Arkansas businessman, made significant contributions to the DNC and to Mr. Clinton after Mr. Wang met with the president in the Oval Office on Feb. 6, 1996.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>According to Federal Election Commission records, Mr. Green gave $50,000 to the DNC on Feb. 7, 1996. Mr. Trie delivered $640,000 to Mr. Clinton's legal-defense fund within a month of the visit. The two men wrote letters of endorsement for the Wang visa, issued by the U.S. Embassy in Beijing.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>At the time of the White House visit, Mr. Wang headed a Chinese arms company known as Poly Technologies Inc., which makes weapons for the Chinese military. The firm was under investigation by the U.S. Customs Service in a major smuggling operation, and it had been identified by agents as a supplier of 2,000 AK-47s to drug dealers and street gangs in the United States.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>"The granting of a visa to the chairman of a weapons-trading company owned by the Chinese military is a matter of great concern," Mr. Solomon said.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Congressional probes of the Lippo Group have since expanded to include a look at the holding company headed by Mr. Wang, known as the Poly Group.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Mr. Green has not returned calls for comment. Mr. Trie and Mr. Huang have not been available.</TD></TR></TABLE> <TD ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top COLSPAN=1 ROWSPAN=1><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=9><TR ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top> <TD ALIGN=left VALIGN=Top COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1"><IMG SRC="../images/vertical.gif" WIDTH=9 HEIGHT=60 ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="" border=0></TD></TR></TABLE> <TD ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top COLSPAN=1 ROWSPAN=1><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=180><TR ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top><TD ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top COLSPAN=1 ROWSPAN=1><A HREF="mailto:wtadvt@wt.infi.net"><IMG SRC="../ads/house_ad.180.gif" WIDTH=180 HEIGHT=60 ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="TWT House Ad 1" border=0></A></TD></TD></TABLE></TD></TD></TABLE><center><p><a href="#linkTOP">Go back to the top of this article.</A></center></TD></TR>
