<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Washington Times-Exclusive</TITLE></HEAD><BODY><P><!-- HTML Copyright (c) 1996 The Washington Times -->
<!-- Jamie White-->
<!-- webmastr@wt.infi.net -->
<A NAME="linkTOP"><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#ff0800"
VLINK="#6f6f6f" ALINK="#000000"></A>
<center><NOBR><IMG SRC="../images/twtbanner.gif" WIDTH=375 HEIGHT=42 ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="The Washington Times" border=0>
<A HREF="../aboutNWE.html">
<IMG SRC="images/exclusive.gif" WIDTH=145 HEIGHT=42 ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="Exclusive" border=0></A>
</NOBR>
<IMG SRC="../images/nwe.redrule.gif" WIDTH=520 HEIGHT=24 ALIGN=MIDDLE border=0><BR><NOBR><font size=-1>Published in Washington, D.C.&#009;<B>February 9, 1997 -- Edition</B>&#009;<IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=0>"America's Newspaper"<BR></font></NOBR><A HREF="buttons.3.gif.map"><MAP NAME="clientmap2"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="436,1,519,18" HREF="../watch/watch.html"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="351,1,428,16" HREF="../letters/letters.html"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="263,0,345,19" HREF="exclusive.html"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="177,1,257,18" HREF="culture.html"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="90,0,172,19" HREF="#linkTOP"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="2,1,86,18" HREF="../index.html"></MAP><IMG SRC="images/buttons.3.gif" WIDTH=520 HEIGHT=19 ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="Navigation Bar graphic, see text links below." border=0 USEMAP="#clientmap2" ISMAP></A><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif"  ALIGN=top WIDTH=0 HEIGHT=8><BR><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=520><TR ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top> <TD ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top COLSPAN="3" ROWSPAN="5"><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=325><TR ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top> <TD ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1"><FONT SIZE=6>Hillary denies<BR>backing database<BR></FONT><ALIGN=Left><HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=100% ALIGN=Center NOSHADE><ALIGN=Left>By Paul Bedard <ALIGN=Left> <BR><font size=1>THE WASHINGTON TIMES<HR SIZE=1 WIDTH=100% ALIGN=Center NOSHADE></font><IMG SRC="../images/cap.H.gif" alt=H border=0 align=left height=34>illary Rodham Clinton on Jan. 30 denied playing any role in creating a secret database of donors and supporters, despite internal papers putting her at the head of the project. <BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Several White House documents obtained Jan. 30 by The Washington Times indicate that Mrs. Clinton and the president ordered the database in 1993, and show that Mrs. Clinton was treated to a special system "demo" in 1995.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>"I would doubt that I was the person who ordered it," Mrs. Clinton told reporters Jan. 30. A former Democratic fund-raiser said he tapped the database despite strict laws prohibiting the White House from sharing the information, culled at taxpayers' expense, with political groups.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>"It struck me as something we needed ... and that's all I know about it," she said of the $638,000 computer system that holds about 350,000 names of supporters, campaign donors and visitors to the White House.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>But Marsha Scott, a longtime Clinton friend and aide who was put in charge of the project, said in several memos that the first lady made creation of the database her No. 1 project.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>"As you know, I am working on establishing a master database in the White House. Both the president and the first lady have asked me to make this my top priority," Miss Scott wrote on Dec. 7, 1993, to Thomas F. "Mack" McLarty, then chief of staff.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>"The president and the first lady want this done," she demanded in a confidential Jan. 26, 1994, memo to longtime Clinton aide Bruce Lindsey.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Five days later, David Watkins, then director of administration for the White House, said in a memo stamped "privileged and confidential" and "eyes only" that the first lady's office would be among the first to get the database when completed.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>White House spokesman Barry Toiv said that he was "not aware" that the first family thought the database was a top priority, other than to compile a list of supporters to invite to the White House.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>"The first lady and president believed it was important in order to be sure that the people they wanted to have at the White House were taken care of," Mr. Toiv said.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>The list initially was to include political supporters and members of President Clinton's "rapid response" political attack team but was later expanded to hundreds of categories, including people who jogged with the president and major donors. It even included lists of donors to unrelated Senate campaigns, according to a copy provided to The Times.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>The existence of the database was first revealed by The Washington Times last summer.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Federal laws, especially the Hatch Act, prohibit the White House from sharing the information in the list with the Democratic Party.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>But another memo obtained by The Washington Times shows that the Democratic National Committee got the list in 1994 as part of their program to send out White House Christmas cards.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Mr. Toiv said that the 1994 Christmas-card list was different from the database of political supporters sought by the first lady.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>The Jan. 30 Los Angeles Times, meanwhile, quoted Truman Arnold, a Texas oilman and former DNC finance chairman, as saying he used the database.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>"I started checking back with the White House just as a routine matter," he told the Times. "It didn't seem to be very privileged to me. It was open to a lot of people."<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>His comments shocked the administration, which is grappling with other charges that it used the White House to raise money in potential violation of federal laws and doled out invitations to special White House events to big donors.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>The DNC issued a statement for Mr. Arnold in which he denied knowing about the database. It included a statement by DNC spokeswoman Amy Weiss Tobe claiming that the party never tapped the database.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Rep. David M. McIntosh, Indiana Republican, is probing the uses of the database, nicknamed "big brother," for the House Government Reform and Oversight Committee.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>He said in an interview that the White House has repeatedly refused to release unedited information about the system and the full committee may seek a subpoena for it this week.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>"The database was probably the central brain in their effort to sell the White House" in the re-election campaign, Mr. McIntosh said.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>The lawmaker said he plans to call Mr. Arnold in for an interview by the committee.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Mr. Toiv on Jan. 30 denied that the administration broke any laws and said the DNC was allowed extremely restricted access to the database.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>"The database was not used by the White House to -- for any sort of fund-raising capacity," said Mr. Toiv, rejecting the suggestions by Mr. Arnold that he used the information system to contact donors.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>He said the database could be used only for "official purposes" such as preparing lists of people to invite to social functions.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>In those cases, said Mr. Toiv, the DNC would have a role. "If the DNC, in the context of putting together a list of people that they might want to ask to be invited to an event here, asked the question 'Was this particular person invited to previous events? Or did this person previously attend events at the White House?' then it would be entirely appropriate for the Social Office to answer that question," he said.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>The spokesman said that the database included skimpy information on each person, including date of birth, Social Security number and reason for attending a White House event.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>But pages of the database shown to The Washington Times show that the White House kept track of donors and identified them with a dollar sign and one entry carried the notation, "major contributor to the DNC."</TD></TR></TABLE> <TD ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top COLSPAN=1 ROWSPAN=1><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=9><TR ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top> <TD ALIGN=left VALIGN=Top COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1"><IMG SRC="../images/vertical.gif" WIDTH=9 HEIGHT=60 ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="" border=0></TD></TR></TABLE> <TD ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top COLSPAN=1 ROWSPAN=1><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=180><TR ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top><TD ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top COLSPAN=1 ROWSPAN=1><A HREF="mailto:wtadvt@wt.infi.net"><IMG SRC="../ads/house_ad.180.gif" WIDTH=180 HEIGHT=60 ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="TWT House Ad 1" border=0></A></TD></TD></TABLE></TD></TD></TABLE><center><p><a href="#linkTOP">Go back to the top of this article.</A></center></TD></TR>
