<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>The Washington Times-Watch this space...</TITLE></HEAD><BODY><P><!-- HTML Copyright (c) 1996 The Washington Times -->
<!-- Jamie White-->
<!-- webmastr@wt.infi.net -->
<A NAME="linkTOP"><BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" TEXT="#000000" LINK="#ff0800"
VLINK="#6f6f6f" ALINK="#000000"></A>
<center><IMG SRC="../images/twtbanner.gif" WIDTH=375 HEIGHT=42 ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="The Washington Times" border=0><BR>
<IMG SRC="../images/nwe.redrule.gif" WIDTH=520 HEIGHT=24 ALIGN=MIDDLE border=0><BR><NOBR><font size=-1>Published in Washington, D.C.<IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=80 HEIGHT=0>&#009;<B>November 10, 1996 -- Edition</B>&#009;<IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=80 HEIGHT=0>"America's Newspaper"<BR></font></NOBR><A HREF="buttons.3.gif.map"><MAP NAME="clientmap1"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="436,1,519,18" HREF="#linkTOP"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="351,1,428,16" HREF="../letters/letters.html"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="263,0,345,19" HREF="../stories/exclusive.html"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="177,1,257,18" HREF="../stories/culture.html"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="90,0,172,19" HREF="../stories/top.html"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="2,1,86,18" HREF="../index.html"></MAP><IMG SRC="images/buttons.3.gif" WIDTH=520 HEIGHT=19 ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="Navigation Bar graphic, see text links below." border=0 USEMAP="#clientmap1" ISMAP></A><BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif"  ALIGN=top WIDTH=0 HEIGHT=8><BR><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=520><TR ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top> <TD ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top COLSPAN="3" ROWSPAN="5"><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=325><TR ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top> <TD ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1"><center><font size=7><I>Watch This Space<BR></I></font><FONT SIZE=4>News about <I>The Washington Times</I></FONT></center><FONT SIZE=6><center>People of The Times<BR></FONT><B>Celebrated editor celebrates his 70th</center></B> <BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Outrageous. Insufferable. Unique. Legendary. Courageous. Magnifique.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>By evening's end, the Oct. 22 birthday dinner roast of Arnaud de Borchgrave, the last of the swashbuckling foreign correspondents and the former editor in chief of The Washington Times, was a rich ragout of deliciously conflicting emotions.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Amusement was combined with admiration, together with teasing tributes to the man celebrated for his derring-do -- what Abe Rosenthal, formerly the executive editor of the New York Times and now a columnist there, cited as bravery beyond the call of duty -- and impeccable sang-froid, as well as a wardrobe beyond envy.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Ben Bradlee, the former executive editor of The Washington Post and now the vice president at large, recalled that he was Arnaud's successor as Paris bureau chief of Newsweek. "I have more in common with Wes Pruden than either of us would care to admit. We both succeeded Arnaud. When all is said and done, Arnaud is a pro, a rogue with great charm and wit."<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>"Life begins again at 70," in the words of the tribute from Boutros Boutros-Ghali, secretary-general of the United Nations, brought to the party by his wife, Leia, and this was confirmed by the bonhomie rampant in the ballroom at The Washington Times, attended by 225 colleagues, friends and fans who had flown in from as far away as London and Dubai to honor the man needled as "a legend in his own mind."<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>The Belgian-born count, who renounced a title to embrace U.S. citizenship and a career covering 17 wars in 90 nations, was roasted to a gentle turn between courses by Mr. Bradlee; Osborn Elliott, former editor in chief of Newsweek who was once Arnaud's boss; columnist Taki Theodoracopoulos; and David Abshire, president of the Center for Strategic and International Studies (CSIS) and a former assistant secretary of state and U.S. ambassador to NATO. The party was hosted by Dong Moon Joo, the president of The Washington Times.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Mr. Elliott called Mr. de Borchgrave "an irreproachable reporter" and "the only person I know who could plant a story about himself just to see how long it would take to come back to him."<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Mr. Bradlee recalled their days in Newsweek's Paris bureau when Mr. de Borchgrave was Mr. Bradlee's boss, full of stories of such one-upmanship as hiring limos of a size too large to fit between the gates of the estates of the titled people Arnaud was sent to interview. This was Mr. Bradlee's first visit to the newspaper with whom he has traded pointed barbs and sharpened needles over the years, and he was introduced by Wesley Pruden, the editor in chief of The Times, as "a man who has been an inspiration to us at The Times, sort of, particularly in the lean early years when he taught us what Dr. Johnson meant when he said that the prospect of hanging focuses the mind in a wonderful way."<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Grace under fire never being his problem, the man who is now the editor at large of The Times and resident foreign-policy expert at CSIS, returned roaster-toaster witticisms with some of his own, culled from a lifetime of experience in a trade he learned from the ground up, first as a clerk at United Press.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>"The operative word is truth," he said. "When you learn to fake that, the rest is easy," he said, quoting the slogan that "'Life is really what happens when you make other plans.' I was one of those lucky ones."<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>Much of the party's zip and flair was credited to Mr. de Borchgrave's wife, Alexandra, radiant in red Chanel. She gathered a cross section of movers and shakers who dance almost as well as they deliver bons mots. A '50s and '60s band, the Hubcaps, played what Mr. Pruden, the emcee, called "what some of us here remember as music."<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>"It was as sophisticated a gathering as anything put together in this city for a long time," State Department official Patrick Daly said. "I could have spent an entire evening with everyone at each table."<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0>If so, he might have talked with ambassadors from Britain, Belgium, Canada, Cyprus, Switzerland, Brazil, Egypt, the Netherlands, Morocco, Thailand, Italy and Qatar; author Christopher Buckley; author and journalist Sally Quinn; television's Sam Donaldson and his journalist wife, Jan Smith; scientific entrepreneur William Haseltine; and such past White House and administration luminaries as Robert Mosbacher, Zbigniew Brzezinski, Fred Malek, Frank Carlucci, Boyden Gray, Lloyd Hand, Robert Kimmitt, Richard Allen, James Schlesinger and William Simon; journalist-historian Michael Beschloss; and such other high-profile journalists as Daniel Schorr, William Safire, Tony Snow, William Tuohy, Emmett Tyrrell, Bernard Kalb and Georgie Anne Geyer.<BR><IMG SRC="../images/nop.gif" ALT="" ALIGN=top WIDTH=30 HEIGHT=0><I>By Ann Geracimos</I></TD></TR></TABLE> <TD ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top COLSPAN=1 ROWSPAN=1><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=12><TR ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top> <TD ALIGN=left VALIGN=Top COLSPAN="1" ROWSPAN="1"><IMG SRC="../images/vertical.gif" WIDTH=9 HEIGHT=60 ALIGN=MIDDLE ALT="" border=0></TD></TR></TABLE> <TD ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top COLSPAN=1 ROWSPAN=1><TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=0 WIDTH=180><TR ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top><TD ALIGN=Left VALIGN=Top COLSPAN=1 ROWSPAN=1><A HREF="about.map"><MAP NAME="clientmap2"><AREA SHAPE=RECT COORDS="1,3,180,59" HREF="aboutnwe.html"></MAP><IMG SRC="images/about.gif" WIDTH=180 HEIGHT=60 ALIGN=MIDDLE border=0 USEMAP="#clientmap2" ISMAP></A></TD></TD></TABLE></TD></TD></TABLE><center><p><a href="#linkTOP">Go back to the top of this page.</A></center></TD></TR>
