<CENTER>
<img src="/nationalreview/images/outrage.gif" ALT="Outrage du Jour">
<br>
<br>


<HR width=50%> 
<!-----------------Townhall------------------------------>
<I>February 8, 1997</I></center>
<BR>
<BR>

<P><center>
<H2>"Tribal Chiefs in Executive Suites"</H2><br>
</CENTER>
<P>
<blockquote>

"Deregulation often is a cost-saver, but in the hands of a bureaucracy, it can lead to additional waste. Consider the Department of Housing and Urban Development's Native American Housing Program, which has enjoyed aspects of regulatory freedom in the last three years. The program was designed to remedy poor housing conditions among tribes, but instead, the agency has poured millions of tax dollars into upscale housing for tribe officials.
<P>
"Since 1992, the Department of Housing and Urban Development, or HUD, has been transferring control of this program from Washington to the tribes, a decision that appears to reflect a commitment to federalism, a return of governmental power to the states and local areas. But a six-month investigation by <I>The Seattle Times</I> recently found that tribal housing officials, many in northwestern states, skimmed program funds and used them to upgrade their own real estate. Among the findings:
<P>
<LI> A tribal official in Washington State built a house worth $400,000, with grants intended for low-income tribe members.
<P>
<LI> Also in Washington, $800,000 in HUD funds earmarked for emergency home repairs went to custom remodel ten houses.
<P>
<LI> In Idaho, $1.8 million from HUD was spent building four large houses.
"New England also had its fair share of waste. A tribe in Connecticut that earns$1 million a day through its casino and has no low-income members received a $1.5 million HUD grant, which it is using to build fifteen large houses."
<P>
          David Wagner, <I>Insight</I>, February 10, 1997

</blockquote>
<!------------------------------------------------------------>
<P>
