HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Saturday, 08-Feb-97 07:14:59 GMT
Last-modified: Tuesday, 28-Jan-97 15:39:13 GMT
Content-length: 6647
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html> 
<head> 
<title>IDEOLOGY OR PARTISANSHIP FOR THE GOP?</title> 
</head> 
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg"> 
<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE> 
<center><h2>IDEOLOGY OR PARTISANSHIP FOR THE GOP?</h2></center> 
<center><a href="/townhall/columnists/pascoe.html"><i>Bill Pascoe</i></center></a>
<p>          
Ideology, or partisanship?  Which is more important for Republicans trying to win elections?  For those concerned with such deep thoughts, last Friday was a day to behold.  Within a span of just a few hours, three events occurred that signaled the supremacy of one vision and the failure of the other:  at the White House, Robert J. Dole was awarded the Presidential Medal of Freedom; on Capitol Hill, Speaker Newt Gingrich's ethics case was argued before the House Ethics Committee; and uptown, at the Renaissance Hotel, a new chairman of the Republican National Committee was elected to replace Haley Barbour.
<p>
These unrelated events highlighted the three different wings of the Republican Party -- the presidential wing, the congressional wing, and the state and local wing -- and their conflicting answers to the question stated above.  The presidential wing has taken the view in the last two elections that simple partisanship is enough, and has failed; the congressional and state and local wings have taken the view that ideology is paramount, and have achieved historic successes.
<p>
To begin, Mr. Dole's award.  Mr. Dole represents both the best and the worst of the Republican Party at the presidential level: the best, in that truly no man loves his country, and made more sacrifices for it, than he.  But at the same time, he represents the worst of the GOP: the stoic, harsh image; the near-obsession with balancing budgets at the cost of all else (even if it means increasing taxes on a regular basis); the fuzziness about ideology and Athe vision thing. 
<p>
Mr. Dole's Republican Party was a party that offered only a cheaper version of the Democratic vision of bigger government, and one that would be paid for as we go along, thank you very much.  It was a party that felt uncomfortable talking about the things that win elections -- the social issues.  And it was a party that lost the last two presidential elections.
<p>
On Capitol Hill, meanwhile, we were hearing the full charges against Mr. Gingrich.  While the controversy over whether or not he took liberties with arcane tax laws (and his resulting fine) will attract the most attention, what was most significant about Friday's hearing was the defense offered by his counsel, Randy Evans, who gave a detailed explanation of the difference between the Party and Athe [conservative] movement.
<p>
Critics of the Speaker, Mr. Evans stated, fundamentally misunderstand the nature of what the Speaker was doing in the early part of this decade.  They focus on what they believe to be the use of tax-exempt charitable organizations to further a partisan goal -- when in reality, he pointed out, it was precisely the other way around:  the Speaker intended to use partisan organizations to achieve the supremacy of the movement and its ideological vision.  Using charitable foundations was not a means to achieve a desired partisan end, to wit, Republican victory; rather, a Republican victory was the means to achieve the desired IDEOLOGICAL end, to wit, conservative dominance over the intellectual and political life of the nation.
<p>
This is not merely a semantic distinction, as it goes to the very core of the Republican Party's strength, and why it will remain strong so as long as -- AND ONLY TO THE EXTENT TO WHICH -- it is the political vehicle through which the conservative movement manifests its political power.
<p>
The validity of this statement can be seen in recent election returns: when the GOP put forth a presidential candidate with a conservative vision who ran an ideological campaign (as it did with Ronald Reagan in 1980 and 1984, and even George Bush in 1988), it won; when it put forth a presidential candidate with no conservative vision who failed to run an ideological campaign (as it did with Mr. Bush in 1992 and Mr. Dole in 1996), it lost.
<p>
Meanwhile, Republicans became the dominant party at the congressional and gubernatorial levels in the last two election cycles precisely by running ideological campaigns.  The result was the Republican capture of the Congress for the first time in four decades and a near-doubling of the number of Republican governors.
<p>
All of which brings us to the election of James Nicholson of Colorado to replace outgoing national chairman Haley Barbour.  Unlike Mr. Barbour's predecessor, Rich Bond -- who in his farewell address to the committee four years ago warned Republicans about the political Adangers' of the party's principled pro-life stand, and urged its removal from the party platform -- Mr. Barbour understood that by its nature the GOP is a conservative party, and that conservatives will walk away from the party, leaving it an army with many generals and no troops, should it ever abandon its conservative principles.
<p>
Mr. Nicholson, heretofore a little-known national committeeman from Colorado, owes his victory to conservatives on the national committee who blocked New Jersey committeeman David Norcross because he was perceived as too liberal, and former New Hampshire governor Steve Merrill because he was too closely associated with the failing, consultant-driven presidential wing of the party.  A Vietnam veteran who holds to strong pro-life views and backed conservative Texas Sen. Phil Gramm in the 1996 GOP presidential primaries, Mr. Nicholson assumes control of a party that's made extraordinary progress at the congressional and state levels, but needs to get back to a winning message and a winning messenger on the presidential level. 
<p>
By all indications, Mr. Nicholson is a man who understands that ideology, not partisanship, is and should be the key to winning elections.  Here's hoping he can use his influence to ensure that the next GOP presidential nominee comes from the ideological wing of the party.  If he can, he'll be remembered as the man who finished the job Mr. Barbour started.
<P>
<center>* * * * *</center><br>
<P>
<center>
