<P>
<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<b>The Curious Case of Edward Luttwak</b><br>

George Gilder remarked some years back that one of the unforeseen costs of the defense conversion after the Cold War was that military theorists would start trying their hands at domestic policy, with dolorous consequences. He was speaking of Edward Luttwak, who's launched a second career in economic declinism. In the <I>Washington Post</I> over the weekend, he assailed what he called "Central Bankism"i.e., hostility to inflation. This "religion" forgets that deflation is just as bad as inflation, and leads to excessive unemployment. In fact, the evidence suggests that unemployment and inflation are positively correlated over the long run. And his point about deflationwhich he confuses with disinflationis the conventional wisdom of the very central bankers he attacks. What's most surprising about Luttwak's article, however, is what it suggests about the author's political trajectory. He calls the 1996 election "a contest between a far-Right candidate, Bob Dole, and a plain right-wing candidate, Bill Clinton." The mind boggles.



