<HTML>
<TITLE>Why Free Trade Is Good For America - Heritage</TITLE>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<CENTER>
<H3>WHY FREE TRADE IS GOOD FOR AMERICA</H3>

By <A HREF="/heritage/staff/johnson.htm">Bryan T. Johnson</A><BR>
Policy Analyst<BR>
<a href="/heritage">The Heritage Foundation</a><BR>
F.Y.I. No. 127<BR>
January 23, 1997<BR>
<HR WIDTH=50%></CENTER>
<p>
<table align=right width=210 border=1 cellpadding=15 hspace=5 vspace=5>
<tr><td bgcolor=#eeeeff>
<font size="-1"><center><b>Charts and Tables:</b></center><br>
<a href="fyi127c1.gif">Chart 1</a>: Number of Computer Hosts Accessing the Internet<br>
<a href="fyi127c2.gif">Chart 2</a>: Average Tariff Rates and Wealth<br>
<a href="fyi127c3.gif">Chart 3</a>: Economic Wealth and Free Trade<br>
</td></tr></table>

<P>
<DD>
Now that the 105th Congress has convened, new opportunities exist for Washington to reestablish America's global leadership in international trade.<SUP>1</SUP>  During the coming year, several key trade issues will be addressed. Among the most important will be fast-track trade negotiating authority, most favored nation (MFN) status for China, reducing trade barriers between members of the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) and the Caribbean Basin nations, and bringing Chile into NAFTA. All of these issues directly affect America's long-term economic security and competitiveness.
<P>
<DD>
Even though these issues involve lowering barriers to U.S. exports and widening the market for American goods, however, some policymakers remain unconvinced of the practical benefits of free trade. The answer to their concern is simple: Free trade has enabled America to become the economic powerhouse that it is today. Continuing America's free trade tradition will allow U.S. citizens to become even wealthier in the future. It will also help developing countries become wealthier.

<P>
<B>THE BENEFITS OF FREE TRADE</B>

<P>
<DD>
U.S. trade represented a mere 9 percent of gross domestic product in 1960. Today, it accounts for 23 percent of GDP,<SUP>2</SUP> and some 12 million Americans owe their jobs to U.S. exports.<SUP>3</SUP>  Opportunities for overseas sales often affect a company's investment choices, hiring decisions, and research and development expenditures. Over the last three years, export of U.S. goods and services has risen by 20 percent -- about one-third of real GDP growth.
<P>
<DD>
Not only is the growth in American exports important, but so is the composition of the international marketplace in which this occurs. In 1970, for example, 29 percent of U.S. exports went to developing countries. Today, it is some 41 percent. This growth highlights the importance of U.S. trade and investment to the international economy in general, and to the less developed world more specifically. Because trade often is an engine of economic growth, if America fails to regain its leadership role in promoting free trade, the economies of less developed countries could stagnate, reducing the demand for U.S. exports and threatening America's long-term economic security.

<P>
<DD>
An open and competitive international marketplace promotes the economic prosperity of all countries engaged in trade. It does so by allowing businesses to be more competitive, by encouraging innovation, by spreading technological advances, and by increasing wealth. For example:
<P>
<UL>
<LI><B>Free trade broadens the variety of "inputs" available to producers of goods.</B> More and more American companies are importing components and raw materials to manufacture their final products. In the computer industry, for example, American manufacturers of the world's most advanced computers import components like low-tech circuit boards to produce the higher-tech finished products. To produce or purchase all the components they need within the U.S., these companies would have to divert labor, capital, and other resources from the high-end, advanced processes involved in production of their finished goods.
<P>
<DD>
Free trade therefore maximizes a company's ability to produce better products by leaving the production of minor components to countries that do not have high-end manufacturing capabilities. This international division of labor has paid off in many high-tech industries. For example, America now produces more of the technology that makes up the worldwide Internet computer network, and more of the computer hardware needed to access it, than any other country. America also leads the world in the number of computer hosts accessing the Internet (see <A HREF="fyi127c1.gif">Chart 1</A>).
<P>
<LI><B>Free trade increases domestic competition, which in turn spurs innovation. </B>
Supporters of protectionism argue that foreign competition threatens U.S. jobs and the profitability of American firms. In most cases, however, competition forces companies to become more efficient and innovative. Indeed, it is the foundation of the free enterprise system. Without competition, companies are under no external pressure to build better and cheaper products, the innovative cycle breaks down, and companies become bloated and inefficient. In the end, consumers pay higher prices and have fewer good products from which to choose.

<P>
<DD>
The U.S. automobile industry is an example of how foreign competition has helped to propel American companies to world leadership. Despite years of trade protection, U.S. auto manufacturers have endured competition from Japanese and European auto manufacturers. This competition came not from imports; it came from Japanese and European plants located in the U.S. During the 1980s, as the Japanese were outproducing and outselling their American counterparts, Detroit responded by building better, higher quality cars. Not only are cars produced by these American companies now outselling many Japanese models, but they are becoming major U.S. exports.

<P>
<LI><B>Free trade maximizes comparative advantage and economies of scale.</B> No country can produce all the products that its citizens want to consume. Barriers to trade reduce the ability of companies to focus on the kinds of goods and services they produce best. For example, many Americans used to perform jobs like gluing soles onto tennis shoes or sewing labels onto sweaters; today, more and more Americans are employed producing products like supercomputers, semiconductors, and computer software. Free trade allows American companies to use the better educated and more productive U.S. workforce to produce goods and services of higher value.

<P>
<DD>
The U.S. today enjoys a virtual world monopoly in providing Internet services. A recent survey of the world's 50 largest Internet services companies, according to the industry magazine <I>Interactive Week</I>, found that all are American firms.<SUP>4</SUP>  This is due at least in part to the ability of America's labor force to focus on producing high-tech products.

<P>
<LI><B>Free trade quickens the flow of technology.</B> Most of the products made today by industrialized countries involve technology that did not even exist two decades ago. Much of this recent technology, however, was pioneered and developed outside of the U.S. No one country can produce all the technologies necessary for the development of new and innovative products. Free trade allows U.S. firms to enter into crucial partnerships with foreign firms. These partnerships, called strategic alliances, allow American companies to gain access to, and to benefit from, the new manufacturing, marketing, and distributing techniques that are being developed overseas. These new techniques can then be used to produce new products in the U.S.<SUP>5</SUP>

<P>
<DD>
In the late 1980s, for example, Japan had achieved a commanding lead in the production of circuitry for such products as laptop computers. American firms responded by seeking partnerships with various Japanese firms involved in that production. As a result, those American firms gained firsthand experience in the production of faster and smaller electronic components. This development helped save the U.S. semiconductor industry from bankruptcy.

<P>
<LI><B>Free trade increases the size of markets.</B> Free trade allows American firms to sell their goods to a larger market instead of just within the U.S. Thus, as demand for U.S. products overseas increases, so does American production needed to meet this demand. This allows American firms to hire more workers, pay higher wages, and invest more money in research and development of new products. Trade barriers overseas affect U.S. firms in the same way shutting the doors to the California market would affect a firm in New York. Free trade expands an American company's market, and this in turn expands sales and provides increased capital for that company's future production needs.

<P>
<LI><B>Free trade appears to produce global economic prosperity.</B> While some policymakers may doubt the merits of free trade, the available evidence suggests that the wealthiest countries are those whose borders are the most open to trade, and that the poorest are those whose borders are least open to trade. The available data show, for example, that countries with lower average tariff rates generally are the richest, and countries with higher average tariff rates generally are poorer.<SUP>6</SUP>

<P>
<DD>
There is a statistical correlation between lower tariff rates and higher levels of economic wealth (see <A HREF="fyi127c2.gif">Chart 2</A>). Moreover, the average per capita income level of countries with an average tariff rate of 4 percent or below is over $17,000.<SUP>7</SUP>  By contrast, the average per capita income level of countries with average tariff rates above 20 percent is below $2,000.

<P>
<DD>
Of course, tariffs are not the only forms of protectionism a country can use. A government may have a relatively low average tariff rate but still heavily protect its market. Thus, to demonstrate fully the connection between free trade and economic prosperity, it is necessary to analyze other forms of trade protection that go beyond tariffs and duties. These "non-tariff barriers" include import bans and quotas, strict licensing and labeling requirements, inspection requirements, corrupt customs officials, and strict antidumping and antitrust laws, among others.

<P>
<DD>
While such non-tariff barriers often are hard to measure, The Heritage Foundation has been quantifying them on a global basis for more than three years. Its <A HREF="/heritage/index"><I>1997 Index of Economic Freedom</I></A><SUP>8</SUP> includes an in-depth economic analysis of 150 countries based on ten broad economic factors, including international trade. The international trade component of the <I>Index</I> measures the average tariff rate and non-tariff barriers to trade per country. Using the <I>Index</I> trade scores, it is possible to identify a country's overall level of trade protectionism.<SUP>9</SUP>

<P>
<DD>
It is then possible to compare the individual trade scores with per capita GDP for each country. Such a comparison shows that countries with the lowest barriers to trade also are the richest, while those with the highest barriers to trade generally are the poorest.10  In fact, all the countries scored by the <I>Index</I> and determined to have "low" to "very low" barriers to trade have an average per capita income level of almost $15,000. By contrast, all the countries scored by the Index and determined to have "high" to "very high" barriers to trade have an average per capita income of less than $2,000. <A HREF="fyi127c3.gif">Chart 3</A> shows that countries having "mostly free trade" to "free trade" policies have higher levels of wealth per capita than those countries with "protectionist" to "partly free" trade policies.

<P>
<DD>
Perhaps an increase in a country's wealth precedes its free trade policies; perhaps the reverse is true. Either way, however, the correlation between lower barriers to trade and higher levels of wealth is real. The facts indicate that as countries open their borders more and more to trade, the wealth of their people is more and more likely to grow.
</UL>
<P>

<B>CONCLUSION</B>

<P>
<DD>
The Clinton Administration and the U.S. Congress should understand this relationship: Countries that pursue free trade are more likely to become wealthy than those that do not. This has important implications for the United States. What is good for the developing countries is good for America. Free trade must become a priority for the Clinton Administration and for the 105th Congress. Policymakers need to move quickly in this legislative year to enact important legislation on trade policies that will benefit America. Above all, Congress needs to grant the President fast-track authority to pursue the negotiation of new trade agreements. Armed with the statistical evidence linking free trade with prosperity and economic growth around the globe, policymakers will find it easy to support something that has been part of U.S. foreign policy since America's inception: a strong dedication to free trade.
<P>
<B>Endnotes:</B>
<P>
<OL>
<LI>For an in-depth discussion of steps Congress can take to reestablish America's leadership role, see Stuart M. Butler and Kim R. Holmes, eds., <I>Mandate for Leadership IV: Turning Ideas Into Actions</I> (Washington, D.C.: The Heritage Foundation, 1997), particularly Chapters 11 ("Defining the U.S. Role in Promoting Global Freedom"), 13 ("Defining the U.S. Role in the Global Economy"), and 18 ("Building Support for Free Trade and Investment").
    Executive Office of the President, Council of Economic Advisers, <I>Economic Report of the President: 1996</I>, p. 225.
<P>
<LI>    <I>Ibid.</I>
<P>
