<title>January 21, 1996 Press Release</title>

<body>

<font size=-1>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<br>
January 21, 1996<br>
CONTACT: Kristi S. Hamrick -- (202) 393-2100. For Radio: Kristin Hansen.
</font>

<p>

<center><h2>MEDICAL MARIJUANA<br>
BLOWING SMOKE?</h2></center>

<p>

<b>RICHMOND, VA --</b> Family Research Council Senior Policy Analyst
Robert L. Maginnis testified Tuesday before the Virginia General
Assembly that no reliable evidence exists to support the idea
that so-called medical marijuana is either safe or effective.
Maginnis said the &quot;marijuana for medicine&quot; strategy
that the pro-legalization lobby has spent 25 years developing
is merely a ploy designed to undermine public resolve against
legalization.

<p>

Virginia's legislative hearing is one of several that will be
held around the country at the state level as the concept marijuana
for medical purposes gains nationwide attention.  Twenty-five
states currently have laws permitting the use of marijuana for
so-called medical purposes.

<p>

Maginnis said: &quot;The most frightening aspect of these laws
is the message they send to our children.  At a time when teens'
pot use is skyrocketing, continuing to officially label marijuana
as anything other than a dangerous drug is wrong.&quot;

<p>

Maginnis added:  &quot;Most doctors would never recommend smoking
tobacco to lose weight; foxclub plant for heart failure; or utrebark
for breast cancer.  These materials may contain chemicals with
therapeutic value for the affliction, but doctors would never
think to recommend smoking as a health therapy.  Pot is crude
and impure.  Using it for medicine is like offering a patient
pond water rather than bottled water.  It's bad medicine.&quot;

<p>

Maginnis concluded:  &quot;Laws permitting marijuana as medicine
are not compassionate but a bad practice.  We should never encourage
our doctors to recommend something that is harmful and addictive
when effective therapies are readily available.&quot;

<p>

<b>For more information or scientific studies that expose the
fallacy of so-called medical marijuana call the FRC Media office.

<p>

Bob Maginnis is available for interviews.</b>

<p>

