<br>

<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<center><b>February 8, 1997</b></center>
<HR WIDTH=50%>
<P>
<P>
<blockquote>
<LI> George Will recently reprinted this colloquy on partial-birth abortion between Sens. Rick Santorum (R., Pa.) and Russ Feingold (D., Wisc.). Santorum: "My question is this:   . . . if that baby were delivered breech style and everything was delivered except for the head, and for some reason . . . that baby's head would slip out . . . would it then still be up to the doctor and the mother to decide whether to kill that baby?" Feingold: ". . . the standard of saying it has to be a determination, by a doctor, of health of the mother, is a sufficient standard that would apply to that situation . . ." Santorum: "That doesn't answer the question. Let's assume . . . the head is accidentally delivered. Would you allow the doctor to kill the baby?" Feingold: ". . . That is a question that should be answered by a doctor, and by the woman who receives the advice from the doctor." Later Santorum engaged Sen. Frank Lautenberg (D., N.J.). Santorum: "If the baby was delivered accidentallythe head slipped outwould you allow the doctor to kill the baby?" Lautenberg: "I am not making the decision . . ." Santorum: "But that's what we are doing here, Senator; we are making decision." Lautenberg: "You are making decisions that say a doctor doesn't have" Santorum: "So two inches make the difference as to whether you'll answer that question?" Lautenberg: "No, what makes the difference is someone who has the knowledge and intelligence and experience making the decision . . ." Someone, obviously, who is not a pro-choice senator. Lucky for them there are no bans on partial thought.

</blockquote>


